title: Some of the things a county expert would do
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: A detailed synopsis of what would have been expected of a county agent (county expert). This includes: grow improved seed on the county farm and distribute this seed to the farmers of the county, conduct demonstrations on the county farm, hold short course schools, help with work in the rural schools, supervise cooperative experiments, plant corn with different numbers of kernels per hill, establish a farmers information bureau, organize dairy test associations, organize granges and clubs, and cooperate with existing agencies. Also includes summaries of what was being done in Clinton County, Iowa, and in other countries and states.

description: Handwritten notes and material for the short courses on judging livestock and on horses. The second lecture on horses includes review of previous material, and details an exercise that would have been done during the course. Contains seven pages of notes.

title: Report and comments of Agricultural and Home Economics Extension Work in Iowa
archival_collection: Ralph Kenneth Bliss papers
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: History of extension work from the point of view of Ralph K. Bliss. Includes description, detail, and personal reflection on short courses, demonstration farms, county agent work, educational trains (Corn Trains), farmer associations and organizations, fairs, farmers' institutes, and extension administration, as well as excerpts from other reports. Some explanation of Extension work from Perry G. Holden.
corporate_name_subject: Iowa State College;Iowa State University;Iowa State University. University Extension
subject: Agricultural education;Agriculture;Home economics
